# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computational-geometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The **closest pair of points problem** or **closest pair problem** is a problem of computational geometry: given n points in metric space, find a pair of points with the smallest distance between them.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The closest pair problem for points in the Euclidean plane was among the first geometric problems that were treated at the origins of the systematic study of the computational complexity of geometric algorithms.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Randomized algorithms that solve the problem in linear time are known, in Euclidean spaces whose dimension is treated as a constant for the purposes of asymptotic analysis.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] This is significantly faster than the $O(n^{2})$ time (expressed here in big O notation) that would be obtained by a naive algorithm of finding distances between all pairs of points and selecting the smallest.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] It is also possible to solve the problem without randomization, in random-access machine models of computation with unlimited memory that allow the use of the floor function, in near-linear $O(n\log \log n)$ time.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] In even more restricted models of computation, such as the algebraic decision tree, the problem can be solved in the somewhat slower $O(n\log n)$ time bound, and this is optimal for this model, by a reduction from the element uniqueness problem.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Both sweep line algorithms and divide-and-conquer algorithms with this slower time bound are commonly taught as examples of these algorithm design techniques.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Round the input points to a square grid of points whose size (the separation between adjacent grid points) is d , and use a hash table to collect together pairs of input points that round to the same grid point.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] For each input point, compute the distance to all other inputs that either round to the same grid point or to another grid point within the Moore neighborhood of $3^{k}-1$ surrounding grid points.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Return the smallest of the distances computed throughout this process.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The algorithm will always correctly determine the closest pair, because it maps any pair closer than distance d to the same grid point or to adjacent grid points.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The uniform sampling of pairs in the first step of the algorithm (compared to a different method of Rabin for sampling a similar number of pairs) simplifies the proof that the expected number of distances computed by the algorithm is linear.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Compute the distances from p to all the other points of S and let d be the minimum such distance.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Round the input points to a square grid of size $d/(2{\sqrt {k}})$ , and delete from S all points whose Moore neighborhood has no other points.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The approximate distance found by this filtering process is the final value of d , computed in the step before S becomes empty.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Each step removes all points whose closest neighbor is at distance d or greater, at least half of the points in expectation, from which it follows that the total expected time for filtering is linear.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Once an approximate value of d is known, it can be used for the final steps of Rabin's algorithm; in these steps each grid point has a constant number of inputs rounded to it, so again the time is linear.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] If the bounding box for all points is known in advance and the constant-time floor function is available, then the expected $O(n)$ -space data structure was suggested that supports expected-time $O(\log n)$ insertions and deletions and constant query time.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] When modified for the algebraic decision tree model, insertions and deletions would require $O(\log ^{2}n)$ expected time.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The complexity of the dynamic closest pair algorithm cited above is exponential in the dimension d , and therefore such an algorithm becomes less suitable for high-dimensional problems.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] An algorithm for the dynamic closest-pair problem in d dimensional space was developed by Sergey Bespamyatnikh in 1998.
[src:computational-geometry/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Points can be inserted and deleted in $O(\log n)$ time per point (in the worst case).
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Computational complexity is central to computational geometry, with great practical significance if algorithms are used on very large datasets containing tens or hundreds of millions of points.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] For such sets, the difference between *O*(*n*2) and *O*(*n* log *n*) may be the difference between days and seconds of computation.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] The main impetus for the development of computational geometry as a discipline was progress in computer graphics and computer-aided design and manufacturing (CAD/CAM), but many problems in computational geometry are classical in nature, and may come from mathematical visualization.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] The primary goal of research in combinatorial computational geometry is to develop efficient algorithms and data structures for solving problems stated in terms of basic geometrical objects: points, line segments, polygons, polyhedra, etc.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Some of these problems seem so simple that they were not regarded as problems at all until the advent of computers.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] One could compute the distances between all the pairs of points, of which there are *n*(*n* − 1)/2, then pick the pair with the smallest distance.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] This brute-force algorithm takes *O*(*n*2) time; i.e. its execution time is proportional to the square of the number of points.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] A classic result in computational geometry was the formulation of an algorithm that takes *O*(*n* log *n*).
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Randomized algorithms that take *O*(*n*) expected time, as well as a deterministic algorithm that takes *O*(*n* log log *n*) time, have also been discovered.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] The core problems in computational geometry may be classified in different ways, according to various criteria.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] The following general classes may be distinguished.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] In the problems of this category, some input is given and the corresponding output needs to be constructed or found.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] The computational complexity for this class of problems is estimated by the time and space (computer memory) required to solve a given problem instance.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] In *geometric query problems*, commonly known as *geometric search problems*, the input consists of two parts: the search space part and the query part, which varies over the problem instances.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] The search space typically needs to be preprocessed, in a way that multiple queries can be answered efficiently.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] For the case when the search space is allowed to vary, see *§ Dynamic problems*.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Yet another major class is the dynamic problems, in which the goal is to find an efficient algorithm for finding a solution repeatedly after each incremental modification of the input data (addition or deletion input geometric elements).
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Algorithms for problems of this type typically involve dynamic data structures.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Any of the computational geometric problems may be converted into a dynamic one, at the cost of increased processing time.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] For example, the range searching problem may be converted into the dynamic range searching problem by providing for addition and/or deletion of the points.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] The dynamic convex hull problem is to keep track of the convex hull, e.g., for the dynamically changing set of points, i.e., while the input points are inserted or deleted.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Some problems may be treated as belonging to either of the categories, depending on the context.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] For example, consider the following problem.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] In many applications this problem is treated as a single-shot one, i.e., belonging to the first class.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] For example, in many applications of computer graphics a common problem is to find which area on the screen is clicked by a pointer.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] However, in some applications, the polygon in question is invariant, while the point represents a query.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] For example, the input polygon may represent a border of a country and a point is a position of an aircraft, and the problem is to determine whether the aircraft violated the border.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Finally, in the previously mentioned example of computer graphics, in CAD applications the changing input data are often stored in dynamic data structures, which may be exploited to speed-up the point-in-polygon queries.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] In some contexts of query problems there are reasonable expectations on the sequence of the queries, which may be exploited either for efficient data structures or for tighter computational complexity estimates.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] For example, in some cases it is important to know the worst case for the total time for the whole sequence of *N* queries, rather than for a single query.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] This branch is also known as **geometric modelling** and **computer-aided geometric design** (CAGD).
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Core problems are curve and surface modelling and representation.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] The most important instruments here are parametric curves and parametric surfaces, such as Bézier curves, spline curves and surfaces.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] An important non-parametric approach is the level-set method.
[src:computational-geometry/computational-geometry] Application areas of computational geometry include shipbuilding, aircraft, and automotive industries.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In geometry, the **convex hull**, **convex envelope** or **convex closure** of a shape is the smallest convex set that contains it.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex hull may be defined either as the intersection of all convex sets containing a given subset of a Euclidean space, or equivalently as the set of all convex combinations of points in the subset.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For a bounded subset of the plane, the convex hull may be visualized as the shape enclosed by a rubber band stretched around the subset.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Convex hulls of open sets are open, and convex hulls of compact sets are compact.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Every compact convex set is the convex hull of its extreme points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex hull operator is an example of a closure operator, and every antimatroid can be represented by applying this closure operator to finite sets of points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The algorithmic problems of finding the convex hull of a finite set of points in the plane or other low-dimensional Euclidean spaces, and its dual problem of intersecting half-spaces, are fundamental problems of computational geometry.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] They can be solved in time $O(n\log n)$ for two or three dimensional point sets, and in time matching the worst-case output complexity given by the upper bound theorem in higher dimensions.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] As well as for finite point sets, convex hulls have also been studied for simple polygons, Brownian motion, space curves, and epigraphs of functions.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Convex hulls have wide applications in mathematics, statistics, combinatorial optimization, economics, geometric modeling, and ethology.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Related structures include the orthogonal convex hull, convex layers, Delaunay triangulation and Voronoi diagram, and convex skull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] A set of points in a Euclidean space is defined to be convex if it contains the line segments connecting each pair of its points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For bounded sets in the Euclidean plane, not all on one line, the boundary of the convex hull is the simple closed curve with minimum perimeter containing X .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] One may imagine stretching a rubber band so that it surrounds the entire set S and then releasing it, allowing it to contract; when it becomes taut, it encloses the convex hull of S .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] This formulation does not immediately generalize to higher dimensions: for a finite set of points in three-dimensional space, a neighborhood of a spanning tree of the points encloses them with arbitrarily small surface area, smaller than the surface area of the convex hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] However, in higher dimensions, variants of the obstacle problem of finding a minimum-energy surface above a given shape can have the convex hull as their solution.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For objects in three dimensions, the first definition states that the convex hull is the smallest possible convex bounding volume of the objects.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] It is not obvious that the first definition makes sense: why should there exist a unique minimal convex set containing X , for every X ?
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] However, the second definition, the intersection of all convex sets containing X , is well-defined.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] It is a subset of every other convex set Y that contains X , because Y is included among the sets being intersected.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Thus, it is exactly the unique minimal convex set containing X .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Therefore, the first two definitions are equivalent.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Each convex set containing X must (by the assumption that it is convex) contain all convex combinations of points in X , so the set of all convex combinations is contained in the intersection of all convex sets containing X .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Conversely, the set of all convex combinations is itself a convex set containing X , so it also contains the intersection of all convex sets containing X , and therefore the second and third definitions are equivalent.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In fact, according to Carathéodory's theorem, if X is a subset of a d -dimensional Euclidean space, every convex combination of finitely many points from X is also a convex combination of at most $d+1$ points in X .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The set of convex combinations of a $(d+1)$ -tuple of points is a simplex; in the plane it is a triangle and in three-dimensional space it is a tetrahedron.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Therefore, every convex combination of points of X belongs to a simplex whose vertices belong to X , and the third and fourth definitions are equivalent.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In two dimensions, the convex hull is sometimes partitioned into two parts, the upper hull and the lower hull, stretching between the leftmost and rightmost points of the hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] More generally, for convex hulls in any dimension, one can partition the boundary of the hull into upward-facing points (points for which an upward ray is disjoint from the hull), downward-facing points, and extreme points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For three-dimensional hulls, the upward-facing and downward-facing parts of the boundary form topological disks.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The *closed convex hull* of a set is the closure of the convex hull, and the *open convex hull* is the interior (or in some sources the relative interior) of the convex hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The closed convex hull of X is the intersection of all closed half-spaces containing X .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] If the convex hull of X is already a closed set itself (as happens, for instance, if X is a finite set or more generally a compact set), then it equals the closed convex hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] However, an intersection of closed half-spaces is itself closed, so when a convex hull is not closed it cannot be represented in this way.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] If the open convex hull of a set X is d -dimensional, then every point of the hull belongs to an open convex hull of at most $2d$ points of X .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The sets of vertices of a square, regular octahedron, or higher-dimensional cross-polytope provide examples where exactly $2d$ points are needed.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Topologically, the convex hull of an open set is always itself open, and (in Euclidean spaces) the convex hull of a compact set is always itself compact.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] However, there exist closed sets for which the convex hull is not closed.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] (the set of points that lie on or above the witch of Agnesi) has the open upper half-plane as its convex hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Convex hulls can be defined more generally in infinite-dimensional topological vector spaces, but they may not preserve compactness in these spaces.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Instead, the compactness of convex hulls of compact sets, in finite-dimensional Euclidean spaces, is generalized by the Krein–Smulian theorem, according to which the closed convex hull of a weakly compact subset of a Banach space (a subset that is compact under the weak topology) is weakly compact.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] An extreme point of a convex set is a point in the set that does not lie on any open line segment between any other two points of the same set.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For a convex hull, every extreme point must be part of the given set, because otherwise it cannot be formed as a convex combination of given points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] According to the Krein–Milman theorem, every compact convex set in a Euclidean space (or more generally in a locally convex topological vector space) is the convex hull of its extreme points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] However, this may not be true for convex sets that are not compact; for instance, the whole Euclidean plane and the open unit ball are both convex, but neither one has any extreme points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Choquet theory extends this theory from finite convex combinations of extreme points to infinite combinations (integrals) in more general spaces.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] When applied to a finite set of points, this is the closure operator of an antimatroid, the shelling antimatroid of the point set.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Every antimatroid can be represented in this way by convex hulls of points in a Euclidean space of high-enough dimension.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The operations of constructing the convex hull and taking the Minkowski sum commute with each other, in the sense that the Minkowski sum of convex hulls of sets gives the same result as the convex hull of the Minkowski sum of the same sets.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] This provides a step towards the Shapley–Folkman theorem bounding the distance of a Minkowski sum from its convex hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The projective dual operation to constructing the convex hull of a set of points is constructing the intersection of a family of closed halfspaces that all contain the origin (or any other designated point).
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex hull of a finite point set $S\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ forms a convex polygon when $d=2$ , or more generally a convex polytope in $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Each extreme point of the hull is called a vertex, and (by the Krein–Milman theorem) every convex polytope is the convex hull of its vertices.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] It is the unique convex polytope whose vertices belong to S and that encloses all of S .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For sets of points in general position, the convex hull is a simplicial polytope.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] According to the upper bound theorem, the number of faces of the convex hull of n points in d -dimensional Euclidean space is $O(n^{\lfloor d/2\rfloor })$ .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In particular, in two and three dimensions the number of faces is at most linear in n .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex hull of a simple polygon encloses the given polygon and is partitioned by it into regions, one of which is the polygon itself.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The other regions, bounded by a polygonal chain of the polygon and a single convex hull edge, are called *pockets*.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Computing the same decomposition recursively for each pocket forms a hierarchical description of a given polygon called its *convex differences tree*.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Reflecting a pocket across its convex hull edge expands the given simple polygon into a polygon with the same perimeter and larger area, and the Erdős–Nagy theorem states that this expansion process eventually terminates.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The curve generated by Brownian motion in the plane, at any fixed time, has probability 1 of having a convex hull whose boundary forms a continuously differentiable curve.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] However, for any angle $\theta$ in the range $\pi /2<\theta <\pi$ , there will be times during the Brownian motion where the moving particle touches the boundary of the convex hull at a point of angle $\theta$ .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The Hausdorff dimension of this set of exceptional times is (with high probability) $1-\pi /2\theta$ .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For the convex hull of a space curve or finite set of space curves in general position in three-dimensional space, the parts of the boundary away from the curves are developable and ruled surfaces.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex hull or lower convex envelope of a function f on a real vector space is the function whose epigraph is the lower convex hull of the epigraph of f .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] It is the unique maximal convex function majorized by f .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The definition can be extended to the convex hull of a set of functions (obtained from the convex hull of the union of their epigraphs, or equivalently from their pointwise minimum) and, in this form, is dual to the convex conjugate operation.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In computational geometry, a number of algorithms are known for computing the convex hull for a finite set of points and for other geometric objects.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Computing the convex hull means constructing an unambiguous, efficient representation of the required convex shape.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Output representations that have been considered for convex hulls of point sets include a list of linear inequalities describing the facets of the hull, an undirected graph of facets and their adjacencies, or the full face lattice of the hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In two dimensions, it may suffice more simply to list the points that are vertices, in their cyclic order around the hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For convex hulls in two or three dimensions, the complexity of the corresponding algorithms is usually estimated in terms of n , the number of input points, and h , the number of points on the convex hull, which may be significantly smaller than n .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For higher-dimensional hulls, the number of faces of other dimensions may also come into the analysis.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Graham scan can compute the convex hull of n points in the plane in time $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For points in two and three dimensions, more complicated output-sensitive algorithms are known that compute the convex hull in time $O(n\log h)$ .
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] These include Chan's algorithm and the Kirkpatrick–Seidel algorithm.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] For dimensions $d>3$ , the time for computing the convex hull is $O(n^{\lfloor d/2\rfloor })$ , matching the worst-case output complexity of the problem.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex hull of a simple polygon in the plane can be constructed in linear time.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Dynamic convex hull data structures can be used to keep track of the convex hull of a set of points undergoing insertions and deletions of points, and kinetic convex hull structures can keep track of the convex hull for points moving continuously.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The construction of convex hulls also serves as a tool, a building block for a number of other computational-geometric algorithms such as the rotating calipers method for computing the width and diameter of a point set.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Several other shapes can be defined from a set of points in a similar way to the convex hull, as the minimal superset with some property, the intersection of all shapes containing the points from a given family of shapes, or the union of all combinations of points for a certain type of combination.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Each of alpha shape is the union of some of the features of the Delaunay triangulation, selected by comparing their circumradius to the parameter alpha.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The point set itself forms one endpoint of this family of shapes, and its convex hull forms the other endpoint.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex layers of a point set are a nested family of convex polygons, the outermost of which is the convex hull, with the inner layers constructed recursively from the points that are not vertices of the convex hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex skull of a polygon is the largest convex polygon contained inside it.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] It can be found in polynomial time, but the exponent of the algorithm is high.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Convex hulls have wide applications in many fields.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Within mathematics, convex hulls are used to study polynomials, matrix eigenvalues, and unitary elements, and several theorems in discrete geometry involve convex hulls.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] They are used in robust statistics as the outermost contour of Tukey depth, are part of the bagplot visualization of two-dimensional data, and define risk sets of randomized decision rules.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Convex hulls of indicator vectors of solutions to combinatorial problems are central to combinatorial optimization and polyhedral combinatorics.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In economics, convex hulls can be used to apply methods of convexity in economics to non-convex markets.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In geometric modeling, the convex hull property Bézier curves helps find their crossings, and convex hulls are part of the measurement of boat hulls.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] And in the study of animal behavior, convex hulls are used in a standard definition of the home range.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Newton polygons of univariate polynomials and Newton polytopes of multivariate polynomials are convex hulls of points derived from the exponents of the terms in the polynomial, and can be used to analyze the asymptotic behavior of the polynomial and the valuations of its roots.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Convex hulls and polynomials also come together in the Gauss–Lucas theorem, according to which the roots of the derivative of a polynomial all lie within the convex hull of the roots of the polynomial.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In spectral analysis, the numerical range of a normal matrix is the convex hull of its eigenvalues.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The Russo–Dye theorem describes the convex hulls of unitary elements in a C*-algebra.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In discrete geometry, both Radon's theorem and Tverberg's theorem concern the existence of partitions of point sets into subsets with intersecting convex hulls.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The definitions of a convex set as containing line segments between its points, and of a convex hull as the intersection of all convex supersets, apply to hyperbolic spaces as well as to Euclidean spaces.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] However, in hyperbolic space, it is also possible to consider the convex hulls of sets of ideal points, points that do not belong to the hyperbolic space itself but lie on the boundary of a model of that space.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The boundaries of convex hulls of ideal points of three-dimensional hyperbolic space are analogous to ruled surfaces in Euclidean space, and their metric properties play an important role in the geometrization conjecture in low-dimensional topology.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Hyperbolic convex hulls have also been used as part of the calculation of canonical triangulations of hyperbolic manifolds, and applied to determine the equivalence of knots.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] See also the section on Brownian motion for the application of convex hulls to this subject, and the section on space curves for their application to the theory of developable surfaces.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In robust statistics, the convex hull provides one of the key components of a bagplot, a method for visualizing the spread of two-dimensional sample points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The contours of Tukey depth form a nested family of convex sets, with the convex hull outermost, and the bagplot also displays another polygon from this nested family, the contour of 50% depth.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In statistical decision theory, the risk set of a randomized decision rule is the convex hull of the risk points of its underlying deterministic decision rules.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In combinatorial optimization and polyhedral combinatorics, central objects of study are the convex hulls of indicator vectors of solutions to a combinatorial problem.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] If the facets of these polytopes can be found, describing the polytopes as intersections of halfspaces, then algorithms based on linear programming can be used to find optimal solutions.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In multi-objective optimization, a different type of convex hull is also used, the convex hull of the weight vectors of solutions.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] One can maximize any quasiconvex combination of weights by finding and checking each convex hull vertex, often more efficiently than checking all possible solutions.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In the Arrow–Debreu model of general economic equilibrium, agents are assumed to have convex budget sets and convex preferences.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] These assumptions of convexity in economics can be used to prove the existence of an equilibrium.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] When actual economic data is non-convex, it can be made convex by taking convex hulls.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The Shapley–Folkman theorem can be used to show that, for large markets, this approximation is accurate, and leads to a "quasi-equilibrium" for the original non-convex market.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In geometric modeling, one of the key properties of a Bézier curve is that it lies within the convex hull of its control points.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] This so-called "convex hull property" can be used, for instance, in quickly detecting intersections of these curves.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In the geometry of boat and ship design, chain girth is a measurement of the size of a sailing vessel, defined using the convex hull of a cross-section of the hull of the vessel.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] It differs from the skin girth, the perimeter of the cross-section itself, except for boats and ships that have a convex hull.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The convex hull is commonly known as the minimum convex polygon in ethology, the study of animal behavior, where it is a classic, though perhaps simplistic, approach in estimating an animal's home range based on points where the animal has been observed.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In quantum physics, the state space of any quantum system — the set of all ways the system can be prepared — is a convex hull whose extreme points are positive-semidefinite operators known as pure states and whose interior points are called mixed states.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The Schrödinger–HJW theorem proves that any mixed state can in fact be written as a convex combination of pure states in multiple ways.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] A convex hull in thermodynamics was identified by Josiah Willard Gibbs (1873), although the paper was published before the convex hull was so named.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] In a set of energies of several stoichiometries of a material, only those measurements on the lower convex hull will be stable.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] When removing a point from the hull and then calculating its distance to the hull, its distance to the new hull represents the degree of stability of the phase.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The lower convex hull of points in the plane appears, in the form of a Newton polygon, in a letter from Isaac Newton to Henry Oldenburg in 1676.
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] The term "convex hull" itself appears as early as the work of Garrett Birkhoff (1935), and the corresponding term in German appears earlier, for instance in Hans Rademacher's review of Kőnig (1922).
[src:computational-geometry/convex-hull] Other terms, such as "convex envelope", were also used in this time frame.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] This maximizes the size of the smallest angle in any of the triangles, and tends to avoid sliver triangles.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The triangulation is named after Boris Delaunay for his work on it from 1934.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] If the points all lie on a straight line, the notion of triangulation becomes degenerate and there is no Delaunay triangulation.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] By considering circumscribed spheres, the notion of Delaunay triangulation extends to three and higher dimensions.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Generalizations are possible to metrics other than Euclidean distance.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] However, in these cases a Delaunay triangulation is not guaranteed to exist or be unique.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation with all the circumcircles and their centers (in red).
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation of a discrete point set **P** in general position corresponds to the dual graph of the Voronoi diagram for **P**.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The circumcenters of Delaunay triangles are the vertices of the Voronoi diagram.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] In the 2D case, the Voronoi vertices are connected via edges, that can be derived from adjacency-relationships of the Delaunay triangles: If two triangles share an edge in the Delaunay triangulation, their circumcenters are to be connected with an edge in the Voronoi tesselation.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] For a set **P** of points in the (d-dimensional) Euclidean space, a **Delaunay triangulation** is a triangulation DT(**P**) such that no point in **P** is inside the circum-hypersphere of any d-simplex in DT(**P**).
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] It is known that there exists a unique Delaunay triangulation for **P** if **P** is a set of points in *general position*; that is, the affine hull of **P** is d-dimensional and no set of *d* + 2 points in **P** lie on the boundary of a ball whose interior does not intersect **P**.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The problem of finding the Delaunay triangulation of a set of points in d-dimensional Euclidean space can be converted to the problem of finding the convex hull of a set of points in (*d* + 1)-dimensional space.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] As the convex hull is unique, so is the triangulation, assuming all facets of the convex hull are simplices.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Nonsimplicial facets only occur when *d* + 2 of the original points lie on the same d-hypersphere, i.e., the points are not in general position.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Let n be the number of points and d the number of dimensions.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] From the above properties an important feature arises: Looking at two triangles △*ABD*, △*BCD* with the common edge BD (see figures), if the sum of the angles α + γ ≤ 180°, the triangles meet the Delaunay condition.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] This is an important property because it allows the use of a *flipping* technique.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] This operation is called a *flip*, and can be generalised to three and higher dimensions.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Many algorithms for computing Delaunay triangulations rely on fast operations for detecting when a point is within a triangle's circumcircle and an efficient data structure for storing triangles and edges.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] When A, B, C are sorted in a counterclockwise order, this determinant is positive only if D lies inside the circumcircle.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] As mentioned above, if a triangle is non-Delaunay, we can flip one of its edges.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] This leads to a straightforward algorithm: construct any triangulation of the points, and then flip edges until no triangle is non-Delaunay.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Unfortunately, this can take Ω(*n*2) edge flips.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] While this algorithm can be generalised to three and higher dimensions, its convergence is not guaranteed in these cases, as it is conditioned to the connectedness of the underlying flip graph: this graph is connected for two-dimensional sets of points, but may be disconnected in higher dimensions.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The most straightforward way of efficiently computing the Delaunay triangulation is to repeatedly add one vertex at a time, retriangulating the affected parts of the graph.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] When a vertex v is added, we split in three the triangle that contains v, then we apply the flip algorithm.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Done naïvely, this will take O(*n*) time: we search through all the triangles to find the one that contains v, then we potentially flip away every triangle.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] If we insert vertices in random order, it turns out (by a somewhat intricate proof) that each insertion will flip, on average, only O(1) triangles – although sometimes it will flip many more.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] This still leaves the point location time to improve.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] We can store the history of the splits and flips performed: each triangle stores a pointer to the two or three triangles that replaced it.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] To find the triangle that contains v, we start at a root triangle, and follow the pointer that points to a triangle that contains v, until we find a triangle that has not yet been replaced.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] On average, this will also take O(log *n*) time.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Over all vertices, then, this takes O(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] While the technique extends to higher dimensions (as proved by Edelsbrunner and Shah), the runtime can be exponential in the dimension even if the final Delaunay triangulation is small.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The Bowyer–Watson algorithm provides another approach for incremental construction.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] It gives an alternative to edge flipping for computing the Delaunay triangles containing a newly inserted vertex.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Unfortunately the flipping-based algorithms are generally hard to parallelize, since adding some certain point (e.g. the center point of a wagon wheel) can lead to up to O(*n*) consecutive flips.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Blelloch et al. proposed another version of incremental algorithm based on rip-and-tent, which is practical and highly parallelized with polylogarithmic span.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] A divide and conquer algorithm for triangulations in two dimensions was developed by Lee and Schachter and improved by Guibas and Stolfi and later by Dwyer.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] In this algorithm, one recursively draws a line to split the vertices into two sets.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation is computed for each set, and then the two sets are merged along the splitting line.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Using some clever tricks, the merge operation can be done in time O(*n*), so the total running time is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] For certain types of point sets, such as a uniform random distribution, by intelligently picking the splitting lines the expected time can be reduced to O(*n* log log *n*) while still maintaining worst-case performance.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] A divide and conquer paradigm to performing a triangulation in d dimensions is presented in "DeWall: A fast divide and conquer Delaunay triangulation algorithm in E*d*" by P.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The divide and conquer algorithm has been shown to be the fastest DT generation technique sequentially.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Sweephull is a hybrid technique for 2D Delaunay triangulation that uses a radially propagating sweep-hull, and a flipping algorithm.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The sweep-hull is created sequentially by iterating a radially-sorted set of 2D points, and connecting triangles to the visible part of the convex hull, which gives a non-overlapping triangulation.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] One can build a convex hull in this manner so long as the order of points guarantees no point would fall within the triangle.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] But, radially sorting should minimize flipping by being highly Delaunay to start.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] This is then paired with a final iterative triangle flipping step.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The Euclidean minimum spanning tree of a set of points is a subset of the Delaunay triangulation of the same points, and this can be exploited to compute it efficiently.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] For modelling terrain or other objects given a point cloud, the Delaunay triangulation gives a nice set of triangles to use as polygons in the model.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] In particular, the Delaunay triangulation avoids narrow triangles (as they have large circumcircles compared to their area).
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Delaunay triangulations can be used to determine the density or intensity of points samplings by means of the Delaunay tessellation field estimator (DTFE).
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Delaunay triangulations are often used to generate meshes for space-discretised solvers such as the finite element method and the finite volume method of physics simulation, because of the angle guarantee and because fast triangulation algorithms have been developed.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Typically, the domain to be meshed is specified as a coarse simplicial complex; for the mesh to be numerically stable, it must be refined, for instance by using Ruppert's algorithm.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The increasing popularity of finite element method and boundary element method techniques increases the incentive to improve automatic meshing algorithms.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] However, all of these algorithms can create distorted and even unusable grid elements.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Fortunately, several techniques exist which can take an existing mesh and improve its quality.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] For example, smoothing (also referred to as mesh refinement) is one such method, which repositions nodes to minimize element distortion.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] The stretched grid method allows the generation of pseudo-regular meshes that meet the Delaunay criteria easily and quickly in a one-step solution.
[src:computational-geometry/delaunay-triangulation] Constrained Delaunay triangulation has found applications in path planning in automated driving and topographic surveying.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] In computational geometry, the **point-in-polygon** (**PIP**) problem asks whether a given point in the plane lies inside, outside, or on the boundary of a polygon.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] It is a special case of point location problems and finds applications in areas that deal with processing geometrical data, such as computer graphics, computer vision, geographic information systems (GIS), motion planning, and computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] An early description of the problem in computer graphics shows two common approaches (ray casting and angle summation) in use as early as 1974.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] An attempt of computer graphics veterans to trace the history of the problem and some tricks for its solution can be found in an issue of the *Ray Tracing News*.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] One simple way of finding whether the point is inside or outside a simple polygon is to test how many times a ray, starting from the point and going in any fixed direction, intersects the edges of the polygon.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] If the point is on the outside of the polygon the ray will intersect its edge an even number of times.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] If the point is on the inside of the polygon then it will intersect the edge an odd number of times.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] The status of a point on the edge of the polygon depends on the details of the ray intersection algorithm.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] This algorithm is sometimes also known as the **crossing number algorithm** or the even–odd rule **algorithm**, and was known as early as 1962.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] The algorithm is based on a simple observation that if a point moves along a ray from infinity to the probe point and if it crosses the boundary of a polygon, possibly several times, then it alternately goes from the outside to inside, then from the inside to the outside, etc.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] As a result, after every two "border crossings" the moving point goes outside.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] This observation may be mathematically proved using the Jordan curve theorem.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] If implemented on a computer with finite-precision arithmetic, the results may be incorrect if the point lies very close to that boundary, because of rounding errors.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] For some applications, like video games or other entertainment products, this is not a large concern since they often favor speed over precision.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Most implementations of the ray casting algorithm consecutively check intersections of a ray with all sides of the polygon in turn.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] In this case the following problem must be addressed.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] If the ray passes exactly through a vertex of a polygon, then it will intersect 2 segments at their endpoints.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] While it is OK for the case of the topmost vertex in the example or the vertex between crossing 4 and 5, the case of the rightmost vertex (in the example) requires that we count one intersection for the algorithm to work correctly.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] A similar problem arises with horizontal segments that happen to fall on the ray.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] The issue is solved as follows: If the intersection point is a vertex of a tested polygon side, then the intersection counts only if the other vertex of the side lies below the ray.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] This is effectively equivalent to considering vertices *on* the ray as lying slightly *above* the ray.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Once again, the case of the ray passing through a vertex may pose numerical problems in finite-precision arithmetic: for two sides adjacent to the same vertex the straightforward computation of the intersection with a ray may not give the vertex in both cases.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] If the polygon is specified by its vertices, then this problem is eliminated by checking the y-coordinates of the ray and the ends of the tested polygon side before actual computation of the intersection.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] In other cases, when polygon sides are computed from other types of data, other tricks must be applied for the numerical robustness of the algorithm.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Another technique used to check if a point is inside a polygon is to compute the given point's winding number with respect to the polygon.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] If the winding number is non-zero, the point lies inside the polygon.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] This algorithm is sometimes also known as the *nonzero-rule algorithm*.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] One way to compute the winding number is to sum up the angles subtended by each side of the polygon.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] However, this involves costly inverse trigonometric functions, which generally makes this algorithm performance-inefficient (slower) compared to the ray casting algorithm.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Luckily, these inverse trigonometric functions do not need to be computed.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Since the result, the sum of all angles, can add up to 0 or $2\pi$ (or multiples of $2\pi$ ) only, it is sufficient to track through which quadrants the polygon winds, as it turns around the test point, which makes the winding number algorithm comparable in speed to counting the boundary crossings.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] An improved algorithm to calculate the winding number was developed by Dan Sunday in 2001.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] It does not use angles in calculations, nor any trigonometry, and functions exactly the same as the ray casting algorithms described above.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Sunday's algorithm works by considering an infinite horizontal ray cast from the point being checked.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Whenever that ray crosses an edge of the polygon, Juan Pineda's edge crossing algorithm (1988) is used to determine how the crossing will affect the winding number.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] As Sunday describes it, if the edge crosses the ray going "upwards", the winding number is incremented; if it crosses the ray "downwards", the number is decremented.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Sunday's algorithm gives the correct answer for nonsimple polygons, whereas the boundary crossing algorithm fails in this case.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Similar methods are used in SVG for defining a way of filling with color various shapes (such as path, polyline, polygon, text etc.).
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] The algorithm of filling is influenced by 'fill-rule' attribute.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] The value may be either `nonzero` or `evenodd`.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] For example, in a pentagram, there is a central "hole" (visible background) with `evenodd`, and none with `nonzero` attribute.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] For simple polygons, the algorithms will give the same result.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] However, for complex polygons, the algorithms may give different results for points in the regions where the polygon intersects itself, where the polygon does not have a clearly defined inside and outside.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] One solution using the even-odd rule is to transform (complex) polygons into simpler ones that are even-odd-equivalent before the intersection check.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] This, however, is computationally expensive.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] It is less expensive to use the fast non-zero winding number algorithm, which gives the correct result even when the polygon overlaps itself.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] The point in polygon problem may be considered in the general repeated geometric query setting: given a single polygon and a sequence of query points, quickly find the answers for each query point.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Clearly, any of the general approaches for planar point location may be used.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Simpler solutions are available for some special polygons.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] Simpler algorithms are possible for monotone polygons, star-shaped polygons, convex polygons and triangles.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] The triangle case can be solved easily by use of a barycentric coordinate system, parametric equation or dot product.
[src:computational-geometry/point-in-polygon] The dot product method extends naturally to any convex polygon.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The term "Ray Casting" was introduced by Scott Roth while at the General Motors Research Labs from 1978–1980.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] His paper, "Ray Casting for Modeling Solids", describes modeled solid objects by combining primitive solids, such as blocks and cylinders, using the set operators union (+), intersection (&), and difference (−).
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The general idea of using these binary operators for solid modeling is largely due to Voelcker and Requicha's geometric modelling group at the University of Rochester.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Before ray casting (and ray tracing), computer graphics algorithms projected surfaces or edges (e.g., lines) from the 3D world to the image plane where visibility logic had to be applied.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The world-to-image plane projection is a 3D homogeneous coordinate system transformation, also known as 3D projection, affine transformation, or projective transform (homography).
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Rendering an image this way is difficult to achieve with hidden surface/edge removal.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Plus, silhouettes of curved surfaces have to be explicitly solved for whereas it is an implicit by-product of ray casting, so there is no need to explicitly solve for it whenever the view changes.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Ray casting greatly simplified image rendering of 3D objects and scenes because a line transforms to a line.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] So, instead of projecting curved edges and surfaces in the 3D scene to the 2D image plane, transformed lines (rays) are intersected with the objects in the scene.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] A homogeneous coordinate transformation is represented by a 4×4 matrix.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The mathematical technique is common to computer graphics and geometric modeling.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] A transform includes rotations around the three axes, independent scaling along the axes, translations in 3D, and even skewing.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Transforms are easily concatenated via matrix arithmetic.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For use with a 4×4 matrix, a point is represented by [*X*, *Y*, *Z*, 1], and a direction vector is represented by [*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*, 0].
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Ray casting is the most basic of many computer graphics rendering algorithms that use the geometric algorithm of ray tracing.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Ray tracing-based rendering algorithms operate in image order to render three-dimensional scenes to two-dimensional images.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Geometric rays are traced from the eye of the observer to sample the light (radiance) travelling toward the observer from the ray direction.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The speed and simplicity of ray casting comes from computing the color of the light without recursively tracing additional rays that sample the radiance incident on the point that the ray hit.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This eliminates the possibility of accurately rendering reflections, refractions, or the natural falloff of shadows; however all of these elements can be faked to a degree, by creative use of texture maps or other methods.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The high speed of calculation made ray casting a handy rendering method in early real-time 3D video games.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The idea behind ray casting is to trace rays from the eye, one per pixel, and find the closest object blocking the path of that ray—think of an image as a screen-door, with each square in the screen being a pixel.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This is then the object the eye sees through that pixel.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Using the material properties and the effect of the lights in the scene, this algorithm can determine the shading of this object.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The simplifying assumption is made that if a surface faces a light, the light will reach that surface and not be blocked or in shadow.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The shading of the surface is computed using traditional 3D computer graphics shading models.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] One important advantage ray casting offered over older scanline algorithms was its ability to easily deal with non-planar surfaces and solids, such as cones and spheres.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] If a mathematical surface can be intersected by a ray, it can be rendered using ray casting.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Elaborate objects can be created by using solid modelling techniques and easily rendered.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Light rays and the camera geometry form the basis for all geometric reasoning here.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This figure shows a pinhole camera model for perspective effect in image processing and a parallel camera model for mass analysis.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The simple pinhole camera model consists of a focal point (or eye point) and a square pixel array (or screen).
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Straight light rays pass through the pixel array to connect the focal point with the scene, one ray per pixel.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] To shade pictures, the rays’ intensities are measured and stored as pixels.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The reflecting surface responsible for a pixel’s value intersects the pixel’s ray.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] When the focal length, distance between focal point and screen, is infinite, then the view is called “parallel” because all light rays are parallel to each other, perpendicular to the screen.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Although the perspective view is natural for making pictures, some applications need rays that can be uniformly distributed in space.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For modeling convenience, a typical standard coordinate system for the camera has the screen in the X–Y plane, the scene in the +Z half space, and the focal point on the −Z axis.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] A *ray* is simply a straight line in the 3D space of the camera model.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] It is best defined in parameterized form as a point vector (*X*0, *Y*0, *Z*0) and a direction vector (*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*).
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] In this form, points on the line are ordered and accessed via a single parameter t.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] If the vector is normalized, then the parameter t is distance along the line.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Where n is the number of ray-surface intersections.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The ordered list of ray parameters, *t* [*i*], denote the enter–exit points.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The ray enters a solid at point *t* [1], exits at *t* [2], enters a solid at *t* [3], etc.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Point *t* [1] is closest to the camera and *t* [*n*] is furthest.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] In association with the ray parameters, the surface pointers contain a unique address for the intersected surface’s information.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The surface can have various properties such as color, specularity, transparency with/without refraction, translucency, etc.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The solid associated with the surface may have its own physical properties such as density.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This could be useful, for instance, when an object consists of an assembly of different materials and the overall center of mass and moments of inertia are of interest.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Three algorithms using ray casting are to make line drawings, to make shaded pictures, and to compute volumes and other physical properties.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Each algorithm, given a camera model, casts one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For computing volume, the resolution of the pixel screen to use depends on the desired accuracy of the solution.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For line drawings and picture shading, the resolution determines the quality of the image.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] To draw the visible edges of a solid, generate one ray per pixel moving top-down, left-right in the screen.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Evaluate each ray in order to identify the visible surface *S* [1], the first surface pointer in the sorted list of ray-surface intersections.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] If the visible surface at pixel location (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* − 1, *Y* ), then display a vertical line one pixel long centered at (*X* − ½, *Y* ).
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Similarly, if the visible surface at (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* − 1), then display a horizontal line one pixel long centered at (*X*, *Y* − ½).
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The resulting drawing will consist of horizontal and vertical edges only, looking jagged in coarse resolutions.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Roth’s ray casting system generated the images of solid objects on the right.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Box enclosures, dynamic bounding, and coherence were used for optimization.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For each picture, the screen was sampled with a density of about 100×100 (i.e., 10,000) rays and new edges were located via binary searches.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Then all edges were followed by casting additional rays at one pixel increments on the two sides of the edges.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Each picture was drawn on a Tektronix tube at 780×780 resolution.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] To make a shaded picture, again cast one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This time, however, use the visible surface pointer S[1] at each pixel to access the description of the surface.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] From this, compute the surface normal at the visible point *t* [1].
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The pixel’s value, the displayable light intensity, is proportional to the cosine of the angle formed by the surface normal and the light-source-to-surface vector.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Processing all pixels this way produces a raster-type picture of the scene.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The volume (and similar properties) of a solid bounded by curved surfaces is easily computed by the “approximating sums” integration method, by approximating the solid with a set of rectangular parallelepipeds.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This is accomplished by taking an “in-depth” picture of the solid in a parallel view.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Casting rays through the screen into the solid partitions the solid into volume elements.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Two dimensions of the parallelepipeds are constant, defined by the 2D spacing of rays in the screen.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The third dimension is variable, defined by the enter–exit point computed.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] where L is defined as the length of the direction vector.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Each ${\tfrac {t[i]\ -\ t[i-1]}{L}}$ is a length of a ray segment that is inside of the solid.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This figure shows the parallelepipeds for a modeled solid using ray casting.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This is a use of parallel-projection camera model.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This figure shows an example of the binary operators in a composition tree using “+” and “−” where a single ray is evaluated.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The ray casting procedure starts at the top of the solid composition tree, recursively descends to the bottom, classifies the ray with respect to the primitive solids, and then returns up the tree combining the classifications of the left and right subtrees.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This figure illustrates the combining of the left and right classifications for all three binary operators.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Ray casting is a natural modeling tool for making shaded pictures.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The grayscale ray-casting system developed by Scott Roth and Daniel Bass at GM Research Labs produced pictures on a Ramtek color raster display around 1979.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This figure shows a table scene with shadows from two point light sources.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Shading algorithms that implement all of the realistic effects are computationally expensive, but relatively simple.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For example, the following figure shows the additional rays that could be cast for a single light source.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For a single pixel in the image to be rendered, the algorithm casts a ray starting at the focal point and determines that it intersects a semi-transparent rectangle and a shiny circle.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] An additional ray must then be cast starting at that point in the direction symmetrically opposite the surface normal at the ray-surface intersection point in order to determine what is visible in the mirrored reflection.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] That ray intersects the triangle which is opaque.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Finally, each ray-surface intersection point is tested to determine if it is in shadow.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The “Shadow feeler” ray is cast from the ray-surface intersection point to the light source to determine if any other surface blocks that pathway.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The secondary ray is then processed as a specular ray.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For the refraction formula and pictorial examples, see Whitted’s paper.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Ray casting qualifies as a brute force method for solving problems.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The minimal algorithm is simple, particularly in consideration of its many applications and ease of use, but applications typically cast many rays.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Millions of rays may be cast to render a single frame of an animated film.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Computer processing time increases with the resolution of the screen and the number of primitive solids/surfaces in the composition.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] By using minimum bounding boxes around the solids in the composition tree, the exhaustive search for a ray-solid intersection resembles an efficient binary search.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The brute force algorithm does an exhaustive search because it always visits all the nodes in the tree—transforming the ray into primitives’ local coordinate systems, testing for ray-surface intersections, and combining the classifications—even when the ray clearly misses the solid.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] In order to detect a “clear miss”, a faster algorithm uses the binary composition tree as a hierarchical representation of the space that the solid composition occupies.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] But all position, shape, and size information is stored at the leaves of the tree where primitive solids reside.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The top and intermediate nodes in the tree only specify combine operators.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Characterizing with enclosures the space that all solids fill gives all nodes in the tree an abstract summary of position and size information.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Then, the quick “ray intersects enclosure” tests guide the search in the hierarchy.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] When the test fails at an intermediate node in the tree, the ray is guaranteed to classify as out of the composite, so recursing down its subtrees to further investigate is unnecessary.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Accurately assessing the cost savings for using enclosures is difficult because it depends on the spatial distribution of the primitives (the complexity distribution) and on the organization of the composition tree.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The following are miscellaneous performance improvements made in Roth’s paper on ray casting, but there have been considerable improvements subsequently made by others.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] If the operator at a composite node in the tree is − or & and the ray classifies as out of the composite’s left sub-solid, then the ray will classify as out of the composite regardless of the ray’s classification with respect to the right sub-solid.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] So, classifying the ray with respect to the right sub-solid is unnecessary and should be avoided for efficiency.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] By initially combining the screen-to-scene transform with the primitive’s scene-to-local transform and storing the resulting screen-to-local transforms in the primitive’s data structures, one ray transform per ray-surface intersection is eliminated.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Given a deep composition tree, recursion can be expensive in combination with allocating and freeing up memory.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Recursion can be simulated using static arrays as stacks.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] If only the visible edges of the solid are to be displayed, the ray casting algorithm can dynamically bound the ray to cut off the search.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] That is, after finding that a ray intersects a sub-solid, the algorithm can use the intersection point closest to the screen to tighten the depth bound for the “ray intersections box” test.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This only works for the + part of the tree, starting at the top.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] With – and &, nearby “in” parts of the ray may later become “out”.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The principle of coherence is that the surfaces visible at two neighboring pixels are more likely to be the same than different.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Developers of computer graphics and vision systems have applied this empirical truth for efficiency and performance.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For line drawings, the image area containing edges is normally much less than the total image area, so ray casting should be concentrated around the edges and not in the open regions.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This can be effectively implemented by sparsely sampling the screen with rays and then locating, when neighboring rays identify different visible surfaces, the edges via binary searches.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The jagged edges caused by aliasing is an undesirable effect of point sampling techniques and is a classic problem with raster display algorithms.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Linear or smoothly curved edges will appear jagged and are particularly objectionable in animations because movement of the image makes the edges appear fuzzy or look like little moving escalators.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Also, details in the scene smaller than the spacing between rays may be lost.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The jagged edges in a line drawing can be smoothed by edge following.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The purpose of such an algorithm is to minimize the number of lines needed to draw the picture within one pixel accuracy.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The line drawings above were drawn this way.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] To smooth the jagged edges in a shaded picture with subpixel accuracy, additional rays should be cast for information about the edges.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] (See Supersampling for a general approach.) Edges are formed by the intersection of surfaces or by the profile of a curved surface.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Applying "Coherence" as described above via binary search, if the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* + 1, *Y* ), then a ray could be generated midway between them at (*X* + ½, *Y* ) and the visible surface there identified.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The distance between sample points could be further subdivided, but the search need not be deep.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The primary search depth to smooth jagged edges is a function of the intensity gradient across the edge.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] For the history of ray casting, see Ray tracing (graphics) as both are essentially the same technique under different names.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Scott Roth had invented the term "ray casting" before having heard of "ray tracing".
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Additionally, Scott Roth's development of ray casting at GM Research Labs occurred concurrently with Turner Whitted's ray tracing work at Bell Labs.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] In early first person games, raycasting was used to efficiently render a 3D world from a 2D playing field using a simple one-dimensional scan over the horizontal width of the screen.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Early first-person shooters used 2D ray casting as a technique to create a 3D effect from a 2D world.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] While the world appears 3D, the player cannot look up or down or only in limited angles with shearing distortion.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This style of rendering eliminates the need to fire a ray for each pixel in the frame as is the case with modern engines; once the hit point is found the projection distortion is applied to the surface texture and an entire vertical column is copied from the result into the frame.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] This style of rendering also imposes limitations on the type of rendering which can be performed, for example **depth sorting** but depth buffering may not.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] That is polygons must be full in front of or behind one another, they may not partially overlap or intersect.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The video game *Wolfenstein 3D* was built from a square based grid of uniform height walls meeting solid-colored floors and ceilings.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] In order to draw the world, a single ray was traced for every column of screen pixels and a vertical slice of wall texture was selected and scaled according to where in the world the ray hits a wall and how far it travels before doing so.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The purpose of the grid based levels was twofold — ray-wall collisions can be found more quickly since the potential hits become more predictable and memory overhead is reduced.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] However, encoding wide-open areas takes extra space.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The Raven Software game *ShadowCaster* uses an improved Wolfenstein-based engine with added floors and ceilings texturing and variable wall heights.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The Voxel Space engine developed by NovaLogic for the *Comanche* games traced a ray through each column of screen pixels and tested each ray against points in a heightmap.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Then it transformed each element of the heightmap into a column of pixels, determined which are visible (that is, have not been occluded by pixels that have been drawn in front), and drew them with the corresponding color from the texture map.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] Later DOS games like *id Software's DOOM* kept many of the raycasting 2.5D restrictions for speed but went on to switch to alternative rendering techniques (like BSP), making them no longer raycasting engines.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] The problem has been investigated for various settings: space dimension, types of objects, restrictions on query rays, etc.
[src:computational-geometry/ray-casting] One technique is to use a sparse voxel octree.
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] In computational geometry, a **sweep line algorithm** or **plane sweep algorithm** is an algorithmic paradigm that uses a conceptual *sweep line* or *sweep surface* to solve various problems in Euclidean space.
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] It is one of the critical techniques in computational geometry.
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] The idea behind algorithms of this type is to imagine that a line (often a vertical line) is swept or moved across the plane, stopping at some points.
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] Geometric operations are restricted to geometric objects that either intersect or are in the immediate vicinity of the sweep line whenever it stops, and the complete solution is available once the line has passed over all objects.
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] An application of the approach had led to a breakthrough in the computational complexity of geometric algorithms when Shamos and Hoey presented algorithms for line segment intersection in the plane in 1976.
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] In particular, they described how a combination of the scanline approach with efficient data structures (self-balancing binary search trees) makes it possible to detect whether there are intersections among N segments in the plane in time complexity of O(*N* log *N*).
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] The closely related Bentley–Ottmann algorithm uses a sweep line technique to report all K intersections among any N segments in the plane in time complexity of O((*N* + *K*) log *N*) and space complexity of O(*N*).
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] Since then, this approach has been used to design efficient algorithms for a number of problems in computational geometry, such as the construction of the Voronoi diagram (Fortune's algorithm) and the Delaunay triangulation or boolean operations on polygons.
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] Topological sweeping is a form of plane sweep with a simple ordering of processing points, which avoids the necessity of completely sorting the points; it allows some sweep line algorithms to be performed more efficiently.
[src:computational-geometry/sweep-line-algorithm] The sweeping approach may be generalised to higher dimensions.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In mathematics, a **Voronoi diagram** is a partition of a plane into regions close to each of a given set of objects.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] It can be classified also as a tessellation.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In the simplest case, these objects are just finitely many points in the plane (called seeds, sites, or generators).
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] For each seed there is a corresponding region, called a **Voronoi cell** comprising all points of the plane closer to that seed than to any other.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi diagram of a set of points is dual to that set's Delaunay triangulation.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi diagram is named after mathematician Georgy Voronoy, and is also called a **Voronoi tessellation**, a **Voronoi decomposition**, a **Voronoi partition**, or a **Dirichlet tessellation** (after Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet).
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi cells are also known as **Thiessen polygons**, after Alfred H.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi diagrams have practical and theoretical applications in many fields, mainly in science and technology, but also in visual art.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In the simplest case, shown in the first picture, we are given a finite set of points $\{p_{1},\dots p_{n}\}$ in the Euclidean plane.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In this case, each point $p_{k}$ has a corresponding cell $R_{k}$ consisting of the points in the Euclidean plane for which $p_{k}$ is the nearest site: the distance to $p_{k}$ is less than or equal to the minimum distance to any other site $p_{j}$ .
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] For one other site $p_{j}$ , the points that are closer to $p_{k}$ than to $p_{j}$ , or equally distant, form a closed half-space, whose boundary is the perpendicular bisector of line segment $p_{j}p_{k}$ .
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Cell $R_{k}$ is the intersection of all of these $n-1$ half-spaces, and hence it is a convex polygon.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] When two cells in the Voronoi diagram share a boundary, it is a line segment, ray, or line, consisting of all the points in the plane that are equidistant to their two nearest sites.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The vertices of the diagram, where three or more of these boundaries meet, are the points that have three or more equally distant nearest sites.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Let ${\textstyle X}$ be a metric space with distance function ${\textstyle d}$ .
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Let ${\textstyle K}$ be a set of indices and let ${\textstyle (P_{k})_{k\in K}}$ be a tuple (indexed collection) of nonempty subsets (the sites) in the space ${\textstyle X}$ .
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi diagram is simply the tuple of cells ${\textstyle (R_{k})_{k\in K}}$ .
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In principle, some of the sites can intersect and even coincide (an application is described below for sites representing shops), but usually they are assumed to be disjoint.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In addition, infinitely many sites are allowed in the definition (this setting has applications in geometry of numbers and crystallography), but again, in many cases only finitely many sites are considered.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Sometimes the induced combinatorial structure is referred to as the Voronoi diagram.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In general however, the Voronoi cells may not be convex or even connected.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In the usual Euclidean space, we can rewrite the formal definition in usual terms.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Each Voronoi polygon ${\textstyle R_{k}}$ is associated with a generator point ${\textstyle P_{k}}$ .
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Let ${\textstyle X}$ be the set of all points in the Euclidean space.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Let ${\textstyle P_{1}}$ be a point that generates its Voronoi region ${\textstyle R_{1}}$ , ${\textstyle P_{2}}$ that generates ${\textstyle R_{2}}$ , and ${\textstyle P_{3}}$ that generates ${\textstyle R_{3}}$ , and so on.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Then, as expressed by Tran *et al*, "all locations in the Voronoi polygon are closer to the generator point of that polygon than any other generator point in the Voronoi diagram in Euclidean plane".
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] As a simple illustration, consider a group of shops in a city.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Suppose we want to estimate the number of customers of a given shop.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] With all else being equal (price, products, quality of service, etc.), it is reasonable to assume that customers choose their preferred shop simply by distance considerations: they will go to the shop located nearest to them.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In this case the Voronoi cell $R_{k}$ of a given shop $P_{k}$ can be used for giving a rough estimate on the number of potential customers going to this shop (which is modeled by a point in our city).
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The corresponding Voronoi diagrams look different for different distance metrics.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Informal use of Voronoi diagrams can be traced back to Descartes in 1644.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet used two-dimensional and three-dimensional Voronoi diagrams in his study of quadratic forms in 1850.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] British physician John Snow used a Voronoi-like diagram in 1854 to illustrate how the majority of people who died in the Broad Street cholera outbreak lived closer to the infected Broad Street pump than to any other water pump.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi diagrams are named after Georgy Feodosievych Voronoy who defined and studied the general *n*-dimensional case in 1908.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi diagrams that are used in geophysics and meteorology to analyse spatially distributed data are called Thiessen polygons after American meteorologist Alfred H.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Thiessen, who used them to estimate rainfall from scattered measurements in 1911.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Other equivalent names for this concept (or particular important cases of it): Voronoi polyhedra, Voronoi polygons, domain(s) of influence, Voronoi decomposition, Voronoi tessellation(s), Dirichlet tessellation(s).
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi tessellations of regular lattices of points in two or three dimensions give rise to many familiar tessellations.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The corresponding cells are known as Wigner–Seitz cells.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] For the set of points (*x*, *y*) with *x* in a discrete set *X* and *y* in a discrete set *Y*, we get rectangular tiles with the points not necessarily at their centers.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Although a normal Voronoi cell is defined as the set of points closest to a single point in *S*, an *n*th-order Voronoi cell is defined as the set of points having a particular set of *n* points in *S* as its *n* nearest neighbors.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Higher-order Voronoi diagrams also subdivide space.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Higher-order Voronoi diagrams can be generated recursively.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] To generate the *n*th-order Voronoi diagram from set *S*, start with the (*n* − 1)th-order diagram and replace each cell generated by *X* = {*x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**n*−1} with a Voronoi diagram generated on the set *S* − *X*.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] For a set of *n* points, the (*n* − 1)th-order Voronoi diagram is called a farthest-point Voronoi diagram.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] For a given set of points *P* = {*p*1, *p*2, ..., *p**n*}, the farthest-point Voronoi diagram divides the plane into cells in which the same point of *P* is the farthest point.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] A point of *P* has a cell in the farthest-point Voronoi diagram if and only if it is a vertex of the convex hull of *P*.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The boundaries of the cells in the farthest-point Voronoi diagram have the structure of a topological tree, with infinite rays as its leaves.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Every finite tree is isomorphic to the tree formed in this way from a farthest-point Voronoi diagram.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] As implied by the definition, Voronoi cells can be defined for metrics other than Euclidean, such as the Mahalanobis distance or Manhattan distance.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] However, in these cases the boundaries of the Voronoi cells may be more complicated than in the Euclidean case, since the equidistant locus for two points may fail to be subspace of codimension 1, even in the two-dimensional case.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] A weighted Voronoi diagram is the one in which the function of a pair of points to define a Voronoi cell is a distance function modified by multiplicative or additive weights assigned to generator points.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] In contrast to the case of Voronoi cells defined using a distance which is a metric, in this case some of the Voronoi cells may be empty.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] A power diagram is a type of Voronoi diagram defined from a set of circles using the power distance; it can also be thought of as a weighted Voronoi diagram in which a weight defined from the radius of each circle is added to the squared Euclidean distance from the circle's center.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi diagram of n points in d -dimensional space can have ${\textstyle O(n^{\lceil d/2\rceil })}$ vertices, requiring the same bound for the amount of memory needed to store an explicit description of it.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Therefore, Voronoi diagrams are often not feasible for moderate or high dimensions.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] A more space-efficient alternative is to use approximate Voronoi diagrams.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi diagrams are also related to other geometric structures such as the medial axis (which has found applications in image segmentation, optical character recognition, and other computational applications), straight skeleton, and zone diagrams.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] It is used in meteorology and engineering hydrology to find the weights for precipitation data of stations over an area (watershed).
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The points generating the polygons are the various station that record precipitation data.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Perpendicular bisectors are drawn to the line joining any two stations.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] This results in the formation of polygons around the stations.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] The area $(A_{i})$ touching station point is known as influence area of the station.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Several efficient algorithms are known for constructing Voronoi diagrams, either directly (as the diagram itself) or indirectly by starting with a Delaunay triangulation and then obtaining its dual.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Direct algorithms include Fortune's algorithm, an O(*n* log(*n*)) algorithm for generating a Voronoi diagram from a set of points in a plane.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Bowyer–Watson algorithm, an O(*n* log(*n*)) to O(*n*2) algorithm for generating a Delaunay triangulation in any number of dimensions, can be used in an indirect algorithm for the Voronoi diagram.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] For discrete grid approximations (such as pixel rendering), the Jump Flooding Algorithm (JFA) and its variants are widely used on commodity graphics hardware (GPUs).
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Originally introduced by Rong Guodong in 2006, the standard JFA computes an approximate Voronoi diagram in $O(\log N)$ parallel passes over an $N\times N$ grid.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Subsequent optimizations, such as the 2019 randomized JFA-star variant introduced by Maciej A.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Czyzewski, shift the pass complexity from scaling with grid resolution to the total number of seed points ( n ), achieving faster convergence in roughly $O(\log ^{*}n)$ passes.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Lloyd's algorithm and its generalization via the Linde–Buzo–Gray algorithm (aka k-means clustering) use the construction of Voronoi diagrams as a subroutine.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] These methods alternate between steps in which one constructs the Voronoi diagram for a set of seed points, and steps in which the seed points are moved to new locations that are more central within their cells.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] These methods can be used in spaces of arbitrary dimension to iteratively converge towards a specialized form of the Voronoi diagram, called a Centroidal Voronoi tessellation, where the sites have been moved to points that are also the geometric centers of their cells.
[src:computational-geometry/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi meshes can also be generated in 3D.
